      "topic": "number_algebra",
      "skill_tag": "systems_equations",
      "parts": [
        {
          "label": "a",
          "body": "Use technology to solve the system.",
          "marks": 5,
          "markscheme": [
            {
              "mark": "M1",
              "note": "enter the coefficient matrix and constants into the GDC"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$x = 2$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$y = -1$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$z = 3$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "R1",
              "note": "verify in an equation, e.g. $2 + (-1) + 3 = 4$"
            }
          ],
          "answer": "$x = 2$, $y = -1$, $z = 3$",
          "solution": "Solving with the GDC gives$$x = 2, \\quad y = -1, \\quad z = 3.$$ Check: $2 - (-1) + 2(3) = 9$ and $2(2) + (-1) - 3 = 0$.",
          "verify": [
            "Eq(2 + (-1) + 3, 4)",
            "Eq(2 - (-1) + 2*3, 9)",
            "Eq(2*2 + (-1) - 3, 0)"
          ]
        },
        {
          "label": "b",
          "body": "Hence write down the value of $x + 2y + 3z$.",
          "marks": 2,
          "markscheme": [
            {
              "mark": "M1",
              "note": "substitute the solution"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$2 + 2(-1) + 3(3) = 9$"
            }
          ],
          "answer": "$9$",
          "solution": "$$x + 2y + 3z = 2 + 2(-1) + 3(3) = 2 - 2 + 9 = 9.$$",
          "verify": [
            "Eq(2 + 2*(-1) + 3*3, 9)"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "contextIntro": "The variables $x$, $y$ and $z$ satisfy the system $$x + y + z = 4$$ $$x - y + 2z = 9$$ $$2x + y - z = 0.$$"
    },
    {
      "source": "IB-AAHL-P2-T2-Q4",
      "number": 4,
      "section": "A",
      "maximumMark": 7,
      "topic": "functions",
      "skill_tag": "graphical_solutions",
      "parts": [
        {
          "label": "a",
          "body": "By considering $f(x) = e^{x} - 3x$ at $x = 0$ and $x = 1$, explain why the equation has a solution between $0$ and $1$.",
          "marks": 2,
          "markscheme": [
            {
              "mark": "M1",
              "note": "$f(0) = 1 > 0$ and $f(1) = e - 3 < 0$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "R1",
              "note": "$f$ is continuous and changes sign, so by the intermediate value theorem there is a root in $(0, 1)$"
            }
          ],
          "answer": "sign change of $f$ on $(0, 1)$",
          "solution": "$f(0) = e^0 - 0 = 1 > 0$ and $f(1) = e - 3 \\approx -0.28 < 0$. As $f$ is continuous and changes sign, there is a root between $0$ and $1$.",
          "verify": [
            "Eq(exp(0) - 3*0, 1)",
            "(exp(1) - 3) < 0"
          ]
        },
        {
          "label": "b",
          "body": "State the number of real solutions of $e^{x} = 3x$.",
          "marks": 2,
          "markscheme": [
            {
              "mark": "M1",
              "note": "sketch $y = e^x$ and $y = 3x$ (GDC) — they cross twice"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$2$ solutions"
            }
          ],
          "answer": "$2$",
          "solution": "The line $y = 3x$ meets the curve $y = e^x$ at two points, so there are $2$ real solutions.",
          "verify": [
            "(exp(0) - 3*0) > 0",
            "(exp(1) - 3*1) < 0",
            "(exp(2) - 3*2) > 0"
          ]
        },
        {
          "label": "c",
          "body": "Find both solutions, giving your answers to three significant figures.",
          "marks": 3,
          "markscheme": [
            {
              "mark": "M1",
              "note": "solve $e^x = 3x$ with the GDC"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$x = 0.619$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$x = 1.51$"
            }
          ],
          "answer": "$x = 0.619$ and $x = 1.51$",
          "solution": "Using the GDC to intersect $y = e^x$ and $y = 3x$:$$x = 0.619 \\text{ and } x = 1.51.$$",
          "verify": [
            "Abs(exp(0.619) - 3*0.619) < 0.02",
            "Abs(exp(1.51) - 3*1.51) < 0.02"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "contextIntro": "Consider the equation $e^{x} = 3x$."
    },
    {
      "source": "IB-AAHL-P2-T2-Q5",
      "number": 5,
      "section": "A",
      "maximumMark": 8,
      "topic": "calculus",
      "skill_tag": "area_between_curves",
      "parts": [
        {
          "label": "a",
          "body": "Find the $x$-coordinates of the points of intersection of the two curves.",
          "marks": 3,
          "markscheme": [
            {
              "mark": "M1",
              "note": "set $x = x^2 - 2$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$x^2 - x - 2 = (x - 2)(x + 1) = 0$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$x = -1$ and $x = 2$"
            }
          ],
          "answer": "$x = -1$ and $x = 2$",
          "solution": "$$x = x^2 - 2 \\Rightarrow x^2 - x - 2 = 0 \\Rightarrow (x - 2)(x + 1) = 0,$$ so $x = -1, 2$.",
          "verify": [
            "Eq(-1 - ((-1)**2 - 2), 0)",
            "Eq(2 - (2**2 - 2), 0)"
          ]
        },
        {
          "label": "b",
          "body": "Find the area of $R$.",
          "marks": 5,
          "markscheme": [
            {
              "mark": "M1",
              "note": "area $= \\displaystyle\\int_{-1}^{2}\\big(x - (x^2 - 2)\\big)\\,dx$ (line is above the parabola)"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "integrand $= -x^2 + x + 2$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "M1",
              "note": "antiderivative $-\\tfrac{x^3}{3} + \\tfrac{x^2}{2} + 2x$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "evaluate between $-1$ and $2$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "area $= \\dfrac{9}{2}$"
            }
          ],
          "answer": "area $= \\dfrac{9}{2}$",
          "solution": "On $[-1, 2]$ the line lies above the parabola:$$\\int_{-1}^{2}\\big(x - (x^2 - 2)\\big)\\,dx = \\int_{-1}^{2}(-x^2 + x + 2)\\,dx = \\frac{9}{2}.$$",
          "verify": [
            "Eq(integrate(x - (x**2 - 2), (x, -1, 2)), Rational(9, 2))"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "contextIntro": "The curves $y = x$ and $y = x^2 - 2$ enclose a region $R$."
    },
    {
      "source": "IB-AAHL-P2-T2-Q6",
      "number": 6,
      "section": "A",
      "maximumMark": 8,
      "topic": "functions",
      "skill_tag": "logarithmic_functions",
      "parts": [
        {
          "label": "a",
          "body": "Find $f'(x)$.",
          "marks": 2,
          "markscheme": [
            {
              "mark": "M1",
              "note": "product rule on $x$ and $\\ln x$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$f'(x) = \\ln x + 1$"
            }
          ],
          "answer": "$f'(x) = \\ln x + 1$",
          "solution": "$$f'(x) = 1\\cdot\\ln x + x\\cdot\\frac1x = \\ln x + 1.$$",
          "verify": [
            "Eq(simplify(diff(x*log(x), x) - (log(x) + 1)), 0)"
          ]
        },
        {
          "label": "b",
          "body": "Find the coordinates of the minimum point of the graph of $f$, giving your answer in exact form.",
          "marks": 3,
          "markscheme": [
            {
              "mark": "M1",
              "note": "solve $f'(x) = 0$: $\\ln x = -1$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$x = e^{-1}$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "minimum point $\\left(e^{-1},\\, -e^{-1}\\right)$"
            }
          ],
          "answer": "$\\left(e^{-1}, -e^{-1}\\right)$",
          "solution": "$f'(x) = 0 \\Rightarrow \\ln x = -1 \\Rightarrow x = e^{-1}$, and$$f(e^{-1}) = e^{-1}\\ln(e^{-1}) = -e^{-1}.$$ Since $f'$ changes from negative to positive, this is a minimum.",
          "verify": [
            "Eq(solve(Eq(log(x) + 1, 0), x)[0], exp(-1))",
            "Eq(simplify((x*log(x)).subs(x, exp(-1)) + exp(-1)), 0)"
          ]
        },
        {
          "label": "c",
          "body": "Find the equation of the tangent to the graph of $f$ at the point where $x = 1$.",
          "marks": 3,
          "markscheme": [
            {
              "mark": "M1",
              "note": "$f(1) = 0$ and $f'(1) = 1$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "gradient $1$, point $(1, 0)$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$y = x - 1$"
            }
          ],
          "answer": "$y = x - 1$",
          "solution": "At $x = 1$: $f(1) = 0$ and $f'(1) = \\ln 1 + 1 = 1$, so$$y - 0 = 1(x - 1) \\Rightarrow y = x - 1.$$",
          "verify": [
            "Eq((x*log(x)).subs(x, 1), 0)",
            "Eq(diff(x*log(x), x).subs(x, 1), 1)"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "contextIntro": "The function $f$ is defined by $f(x) = x\\ln x$ for $x > 0$."
    },
    {
      "source": "IB-AAHL-P2-T2-Q7",
      "number": 7,
      "section": "A",
      "maximumMark": 8,
      "topic": "number_algebra",
      "skill_tag": "complex_numbers",
      "parts": [
        {
          "label": "a",
          "body": "Write down $|z|$ and $\\arg z$.",
          "marks": 2,
          "markscheme": [
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$|z| = \\sqrt2$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$\\arg z = \\dfrac{\\pi}{4}$"
            }
          ],
          "answer": "$|z| = \\sqrt2$, $\\arg z = \\dfrac{\\pi}{4}$",
          "solution": "$$|z| = \\sqrt{1^2 + 1^2} = \\sqrt2, \\qquad \\arg z = \\frac{\\pi}{4}.$$",
          "verify": [
            "Eq(Abs(1 + I), sqrt(2))",
            "Eq(arg(1 + I), pi/4)"
          ]
        },
        {
          "label": "b",
          "body": "Use de Moivre's theorem to find $z^{8}$.",
          "marks": 3,
          "markscheme": [
            {
              "mark": "M1",
              "note": "$z^8 = (\\sqrt2)^8\\operatorname{cis}\\!\\left(8\\cdot\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}\\right)$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$= 16\\operatorname{cis}(2\\pi)$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$z^8 = 16$"
            }
          ],
          "answer": "$z^8 = 16$",
          "solution": "$$z^8 = (\\sqrt2)^8\\operatorname{cis}(2\\pi) = 16(1 + 0i) = 16.$$",
          "verify": [
            "Eq(simplify((1 + I)**8), 16)"
          ]
        },
        {
          "label": "c",
          "body": "Find the smallest positive integer $n$ such that $z^{n}$ is a real number.",
          "marks": 3,
          "markscheme": [
            {
              "mark": "M1",
              "note": "$z^n$ is real when $\\arg(z^n) = \\dfrac{n\\pi}{4}$ is a multiple of $\\pi$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$n$ must be a multiple of $4$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$n = 4$ (and $z^4 = -4$)"
            }
          ],
          "answer": "$n = 4$",
          "solution": "$\\arg(z^n) = \\dfrac{n\\pi}{4}$ is a multiple of $\\pi$ exactly when $4 \\mid n$; the smallest positive such $n$ is $4$, and indeed $z^4 = (1+i)^4 = -4$ is real.",
          "verify": [
            "Eq(simplify((1 + I)**4), -4)"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "contextIntro": "Let $z = 1 + i$."
    },
    {
      "source": "IB-AAHL-P2-T2-Q8",
      "number": 8,
      "section": "B",
      "maximumMark": 19,
      "topic": "stats_probability",
      "skill_tag": "expectation_binomial",
      "parts": [
        {
          "label": "a",
          "body": "Complete the probability distribution of $W$: the values are $-2$, $2$, $4$ and $6$. Write down each probability.",
          "marks": 3,
          "markscheme": [
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$P(W = -2) = \\tfrac12$ (odd)"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$P(W = 2) = P(W = 4) = P(W = 6) = \\tfrac16$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "R1",
              "note": "the four probabilities sum to $1$"
            }
          ],
          "answer": "$P(W=-2)=\\tfrac12$; $P(W=2)=P(W=4)=P(W=6)=\\tfrac16$",
          "solution": "An odd result ($1, 3, 5$) has probability $\\tfrac36 = \\tfrac12$ and gives $W = -2$; each even result has probability $\\tfrac16$ and gives $W = 2, 4, 6$ respectively. These sum to $1$.",
          "verify": [
            "Eq(Rational(1,2) + 3*Rational(1,6), 1)"
          ]
        },
        {
          "label": "b",
          "body": "Find $E(W)$.",
          "marks": 3,
          "markscheme": [
            {
              "mark": "M1",
              "note": "$E(W) = \\sum w\\,P(W = w)$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$\\tfrac16(2 + 4 + 6) + \\tfrac12(-2) = 2 - 1$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$E(W) = 1$"
            }
          ],
          "answer": "$E(W) = \\$1$",
          "solution": "$$E(W) = \\frac16(2 + 4 + 6) + \\frac12(-2) = 2 - 1 = 1.$$",
          "verify": [
            "Eq(Rational(1,6)*(2 + 4 + 6) + Rational(1,2)*(-2), 1)"
          ]
        },
        {
          "label": "c",
          "body": "Find $\\operatorname{Var}(W)$.",
          "marks": 3,
          "markscheme": [
            {
              "mark": "M1",
              "note": "$E(W^2) = \\tfrac16(4 + 16 + 36) + \\tfrac12(4) = \\tfrac{34}{3}$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "M1",
              "note": "$\\operatorname{Var}(W) = E(W^2) - [E(W)]^2$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$\\operatorname{Var}(W) = \\dfrac{31}{3}$"
            }
          ],
          "answer": "$\\operatorname{Var}(W) = \\dfrac{31}{3}$",
          "solution": "$$E(W^2) = \\frac16(4 + 16 + 36) + \\frac12(4) = \\frac{34}{3},$$$$\\operatorname{Var}(W) = \\frac{34}{3} - 1^2 = \\frac{31}{3}.$$",
          "verify": [
            "Eq(Rational(1,6)*(4 + 16 + 36) + Rational(1,2)*4, Rational(34, 3))",
            "Eq(Rational(34, 3) - 1, Rational(31, 3))"
          ]
        },
        {
          "label": "d",
          "body": "The game is played $20$ times. Find the expected total winnings and the standard deviation of the total.",
          "marks": 4,
          "markscheme": [
            {
              "mark": "M1",
              "note": "total expectation $= 20\\,E(W)$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "expected total $= \\$20$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "M1",
              "note": "total variance $= 20\\operatorname{Var}(W)$ (independent rolls)"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "standard deviation $= \\sqrt{20 \\cdot \\tfrac{31}{3}} = 14.4$"
            }
          ],
          "answer": "expected \\$20; standard deviation $14.4$",
          "solution": "$$E(\\text{total}) = 20(1) = \\$20.$$ Because the rolls are independent, variances add:$$\\operatorname{sd} = \\sqrt{20\\cdot\\tfrac{31}{3}} = 14.3759 \\approx 14.4.$$",
          "verify": [
            "Abs(sqrt(20*Rational(31, 3)) - 14.4) < 0.051000000000000004"
          ]
        },
